# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alingano-maisu
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alingano-maisu/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Aboriginal people began using dugout canoes from around 1640 in coastal regions of northern Australia.
[src:alingano-maisu/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] They were brought by Buginese fishers of sea cucumbers, known as trepangers, from Makassar in South Sulawesi.
[src:alingano-maisu/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] In Arnhem Land, dugout canoes used by the local Yolngu people are called *lipalipa* or *lippa-lippa*.
[src:alingano-maisu/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Aboriginal canoes were constructed much more easily than previous types of vessels, such as bark canoes.
[src:alingano-maisu/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] This ease of construction played a significant role in the dugout canoes’ widespread use.
[src:alingano-maisu/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] While earlier vessels required a great deal of labor and time-consuming sewing to make, dugout canoes were constructed easily and in a shorter period of time.
[src:alingano-maisu/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] First, one would have to cut down a tree and shape the exterior into an even form.
[src:alingano-maisu/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] The sides of the canoe were shaped in one of two ways.
[src:alingano-maisu/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] They were either carved straight up and down or in a "u" shape, curving in towards the center of the boat.
[src:alingano-maisu/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Next, one would have to dig out the inner wood of the log to make space for the oarsmen to sit and paddle.
[src:alingano-maisu/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] In some early dugout canoes, Aboriginal people would not make the bottoms of the canoes smooth, but would instead carve "ribbing" into the vessel.
[src:alingano-maisu/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Ribbing (literally sections of wood that looked like ribs) was used to stabilize bark canoes, and though not necessary to dugout canoes, was a carryover in the transition from one canoe type to the other.
[src:alingano-maisu/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Both the chopping down of the tree and the digging out of the log were easily done with an iron-axe.
[src:alingano-maisu/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] The wood used in the construction of dugout canoes was essential to its strength and durability.
[src:alingano-maisu/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Sycamores are strong and extremely durable, making them suitable for use in the construction of dugout canoes.
[src:alingano-maisu/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Both sea turtles and dugongs were essential components of the Aboriginal diet.
[src:alingano-maisu/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] The transformation from bark canoes to dugout canoes greatly increased the ability of the tribal hunters to catch and kill both of these types of sea creatures due primarily to a more formidable structure.
[src:alingano-maisu/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Dugout canoes included a stronger and better platform for harpooning that greatly increased the stability of an upright hunter by providing essential footing.
[src:alingano-maisu/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] In order to capture dugongs and sea turtles, the hunters needed to maintain the utmost degree of stealth.
[src:alingano-maisu/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Perfect balance was required and the new dugout canoes gave the hunters this necessary edge.
[src:alingano-maisu/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Additionally, the shift towards using dugout canoes maximized the overall possibilities of seafarers.
[src:alingano-maisu/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Not only did increased sturdiness, speed and stability of Dugout canoes make hunting easier, but these characteristics also allowed for long-distance travel.
[src:alingano-maisu/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Whereas bark canoes had been only used for inland use or travel extremely close to the shore, Dugout canoes offered a far greater range of travel which allowed for trade outside the area of the village.
[src:alingano-maisu/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Dugout canoes were capable of traveling distances over 500 km.
[src:alingano-maisu/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] This new vessel gave the Aboriginal people the ability and opportunity to explore, trade and locate additional resources located outside the central location.
[src:alingano-maisu/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] The widespread use of dugout canoes had many impacts on Aboriginal life.
[src:alingano-maisu/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] The most significant were results of the Aboriginal peoples' ability to hunt larger prey.
[src:alingano-maisu/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] With the strength to transport larger prey over longer distances, dugout enabled the peoples to vastly expand their hunting grounds.
[src:alingano-maisu/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] This larger prey also enabled support of a larger group of people over a longer period of time.
[src:alingano-maisu/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] This increase in the ability to support population led to both population growth and expansion.
[src:alingano-maisu/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] Torres Strait Islander people, another Indigenous Australian group of peoples (who are not Aboriginal), used a different type of boat – a double outrigger, unique to their area and probably introduced from Papuan communities and later modified.
[src:alingano-maisu/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] It was about 14 metres (46 ft) long, with two bamboo masts and sails made of pandanus-mat.
[src:alingano-maisu/aboriginal-dugout-canoe] They could sail as far as 80 kilometres (50 mi) and carry up to twelve people.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] The **Admiralty Islands** are an archipelago group of 40 islands in the Bismarck Archipelago, to the north of New Guinea in the South Pacific Ocean.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] These are also sometimes known as the **Manus Islands**, after the largest island of the chain.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] These rainforest-covered islands constitute Manus Province, the smallest and least-populous province of Papua New Guinea, in its Islands Region.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] The province had a population of 60,485 at the 2011 Census.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] Many of the smaller Admiralty Islands are atolls and uninhabited.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] The larger islands in the center of the group are Manus Island and Los Negros Island.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] The other larger islands are Tong Island, Pak Island, Rambutyo Island and Lou Island to the east, Mbuke Island to the south and Bipi Island to the west of Manus Island.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] Baluan Island, to the south of Manus Island, is the main island of the Pam Islands, where the Baluan-Pam language is spoken.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] Other islands that have been noted as significant places in the history of Manus include Ndrova Island, Pityilu Island and Ponam Island.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] The temperature of the Admiralty Islands varies little throughout the year, reaching daily highs of 30–32 °C (86–90 °F) and 20–24 °C (68–75 °F) at night.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] Average annual rainfall is 3,382 mm (133 in) and is somewhat seasonal, with June–August being the wettest months.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] Manus reaches an elevation of 700 m (2,300 ft) and is volcanic in origin and probably broke through the ocean's surface in the late Miocene, 8–10 million years ago.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] The substrate of the island is either directly volcanic or from uplifted coral limestone.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] The main town in the islands is Lorengau on Manus, connected by road to an airport on nearby Los Negros Island, otherwise transport around the islands is by boat.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] There is little tourism, although the seas are attractive to divers, including Jean-Michel Cousteau who spent time on nearby Wuvulu Island in the 1970s.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] Due to the isolated location, the rain forests of the Admiralty Islands are home to rare and endemic species of birds, bats and other animals, and are considered a separate ecoregion, the **Admiralty Islands lowland rain forests**.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] The majority of the forests on Manus still remain, but some of the smaller islands have been cleared for coconut farming.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] The typical tree species are various *Calophyllum* and *Sararanga* species.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] The 58.5 km2 (22.6 sq mi) Ndrolowa Wildlife Management Area was created in March 1985 south of Lorengau on Manus Island and contains both terrestrial and marine regions.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] A further 240 km2 (93 sq mi) protected area has been established around the highest mountain on Manus, Mount Dremsel, but the level of protection remains undetermined in the UNEP World Database on Protected Areas.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] Three of the bird species endemic to Admiralty Islands have been listed as vulnerable in the IUCN Red List: Manus fantail (*Rhipidura semirubra*), superb pitta (*Pitta superba*) and Manus masked owl (*Tyto manusi*), and the Manus dwarf kingfisher (*Ceyx dispar*) listed as near threatened.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] Three other birds are endemic to Admiralty Islands but are classified as non-threatened or least concern: white-naped friarbird (*Philemon albitorques*), Manus monarch (*Monarcha infelix*) and Manus hawk owl (*Ninox meeki*).
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] The islands are home to two endemic *Cornufer* frogs (*Cornufer admiraltiensis* and *Cornufer latro*) and four lizards, while the emerald green snail of Manus was the first terrestrial snail to be listed as vulnerable by the IUCN.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] Along with New Guinea, the Bismarck Archipelago and the Solomon Islands Archipelago, the Admiralty Islands were first inhabited approximately 40,000 years ago, in the initial wave of migration out of Southeast Asia that also populated Australia.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] This early society appears to have cultivated taro, and to have deliberately introduced wild animals from New Guinea such as bandicoots and large rats.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] Obsidian was gathered and traded throughout the Admiralty Islands archipelago.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] The Lapita culture arose around 3,500 years ago, and its extent ranged from the Admiralty Islands to Tonga and Samoa.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] Its origins are contested, but it may well have been a product of another wave of migration from Southeast Asia.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] Lapita society featured renowned pottery, stilt houses, the introduction of domestic animals such as pigs, dogs, and chickens, and substantial developments in agriculture and boat technology, allowing long-distance trade to develop.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] Lapita society, as a distinct culture and extended trade network, collapsed around 2,000 years ago.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] The first European to visit the islands was the Spanish navigator Álvaro de Saavedra when trying to return from Tidore to New Spain in the summer of 1528.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] Saavedra charted Manus as *Urays la Grande*.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] Its visit was also reported in 1616 by the Dutch navigator Willem Schouten.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] The name 'Admiralty Islands' was devised by Captain Philip Carteret of the British Royal Navy in 1767.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] Between 1884 and 1914 the area was administered as a German colony.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] In November 1914, the islands were occupied by troops of the Australian Naval and Military Expeditionary Force landed from the SS *Siar*.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] A few shots fired from a machine gun on *Siar* over the heads of the tiny German garrison at Lorengau were the last shots fired in the battle.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] After the war, the islands were governed by the Commonwealth of Australia under a League of Nations mandate.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] Japanese troops landed on Manus Island on 7 April 1942.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] In 1944, Japanese forces occupying the islands were attacked and defeated by Allied forces in Operation Brewer.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] Subsequently, a large American airbase and Manus Naval Base was built at Lombrum near Lorengau.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] Following Papuan independence in 1975, the Admiralty Islands became part of Papua New Guinea.
[src:alingano-maisu/admiralty-islands] They became the Manus Province of the Islands Region in Papua New Guinea.
[src:alingano-maisu/alingano-maisu] The concept for *Alingano Maisu* came about in 2001 when two Hawaiian voyaging groups, the Polynesian Voyaging Society and Na Kalai Waʻa Moku o Hawaiʻi, met with Piailug.
[src:alingano-maisu/alingano-maisu] The two hulls of the 56-foot (17 m) vessel were fabricated by the Friends of *Hōkūleʻa* and *Hawaiʻiloa* on Oʻahu and shipped to the Island of Hawaiʻi where Na Kalai Waʻa completed construction of the canoe.
[src:alingano-maisu/alingano-maisu] The Polynesian Voyaging Society provided much of the funding for the voyaging aspect of the project as well as an escort boat to help sail the canoe to Satawal.
[src:alingano-maisu/alingano-maisu] The canoe is home-ported on the island of Yap under the command of Piailug's son, Sesario Sewralur.
[src:alingano-maisu/alingano-maisu] Accompanied by *Hōkūleʻa*, the *Maisu* left Kawaihae, Hawaii, on January 18, 2007.
[src:alingano-maisu/alingano-maisu] After stops in the Marshall Islands, Pohnpei, and Chuuk, the Maisu reached Satawal on March 15, 2007.
[src:alingano-maisu/alingano-maisu] On March 18, while on Satawal, five native Hawaiian navigators on the voyage were inducted into pwo, a sacred Micronesian brotherhood of master navigators.
[src:alingano-maisu/alingano-maisu] In June 2008, Palau Community College announced that there will be a one-year program in traditional non-instrumental navigation on the *Alingano Maisu* under Sesario Sewralur.
[src:alingano-maisu/aloha-festivals] The **Aloha Festivals** are an annual series of free cultural celebrations observed in the state of Hawaii in the United States based on the Makahiki, the beginning of the Native Hawaiian year marked by the sighting of the Pleiades (*Makali'i*).
[src:alingano-maisu/aloha-festivals] It is the only statewide cultural festival in the nation.
[src:alingano-maisu/aloha-festivals] Highlights include the presentation of the Royal Court, a ho'olaule'a in Waikiki, and the Floral Parade.
[src:alingano-maisu/aloha-festivals] Approximately 30,000 people volunteer to plan, organize, and provide labor for the Aloha Festivals each year.
[src:alingano-maisu/aloha-festivals] Their efforts entertain over 1,000,000 people from throughout the state and visitors from all over the world.
[src:alingano-maisu/aloha-festivals] In the spirit of preserving the Hawaiian culture and heritage, the Aloha Festivals were established in 1946 as **Aloha Week** by former members of the local Junior Chamber of Commerce.
[src:alingano-maisu/aloha-festivals] The former manager of the festivals, Goriann Akau, has said, "In 1946, after the war, Hawaiians needed an identity.
[src:alingano-maisu/aloha-festivals] When we started to celebrate our culture, we began to feel proud.
[src:alingano-maisu/aloha-festivals] We have a wonderful culture that had been buried for a number of years.
[src:alingano-maisu/aloha-festivals] The festival was celebrated on six of Hawaii's islands, but in 2008 festival organizers decided to hold most events on Oahu due to a lack of funding.
[src:alingano-maisu/aloha-festivals] There was also the chance that the Floral Parade would be cancelled altogether, but it was saved by private donors and funds from the City and County of Honolulu.
[src:alingano-maisu/aloha-festivals] That was caused by the COVID-19 pandemic, a year which had many disruptions.
[src:alingano-maisu/aloha-festivals] The court is selected from a pool of applicants, all of whom must be of Hawaiian ancestry and of certain ages.
[src:alingano-maisu/aloha-festivals] The festival itself begins with the presentation of the royal court during the opening ceremony.
[src:alingano-maisu/aloha-festivals] The ceremony takes place at Helumoa, a section of Waikiki near the Royal Hawaiian Center.
[src:alingano-maisu/aloha-festivals] The Floral Parade starts at the intersection of Ala Moana Boulevard and Kamakee st. and goes through Waikiki before finishing at Kapiolani Park.
[src:alingano-maisu/aloha-festivals] The parade features p'au riders, marching bands, hula halaus, and that year's Aloha Festival Royal Court.
[src:alingano-maisu/aloha-festivals] The Hoʻolauleʻa is a block party held in Waikiki.
[src:alingano-maisu/aloha-festivals] There is Hawaiian music, hula, and food.
[src:alingano-maisu/aloha-festivals] Attendance is typically in the thousands.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] The **New Zealand Maritime Museum Hui Te Ananui a Tangaroa** is a maritime museum in Auckland, New Zealand.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] It is located on Hobson Wharf, adjacent to the Viaduct Harbour in central Auckland.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] It houses exhibitions spanning New Zealand's maritime history, from the first Polynesian explorers and settlers to modern day triumphs at the America's Cup.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] The museum focuses on maritime stories of both the Auckland Region and New Zealand, with displays covering topics including immigration, trade, design, innovation, leisure, maritime history, Polynesian voyagers, and the history of the America's Cup.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] In addition to displays and art exhibitions, the New Zealand Maritime Museum collections include historic and cultural artifacts, replicas and working heritage vessels.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] The New Zealand Maritime Museum is located on Hobson Wharf on the Auckland waterfront, adjacent to the Viaduct Basin and Princes Wharf.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] The entrance of the museum incorporates the Launchman's Building, a structure built in 1920 which formerly housed a number of small boating companies.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] The old Launchman's Building (Launch Offices) gained a Category II listing from Heritage New Zealand in 1981.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] The main section of the maritime museum in an industrial-inspired structure located on Hobson Wharf.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] Heritage vessels owned by the museum are moored at the museum marina, and launched for sailings around the Waitematā Harbour.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] In 2010, the building won the Auckland Architecture Awards by the New Zealand Institute of Architects.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] Located outside of the Maritime Museum's entrance is *KZ1*, a yacht built to compete in the 1988 America's Cup, gifted to the museum by Fay Richwhite in 1990.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] Currently known as New Zealand Maritime Museum Hui Te Ananui a Tangaroa, the museum opened in 1993 as Hobson Wharf: Auckland Maritime Museum.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] In 1996, the museum was renamed the New Zealand National Maritime Museum, a name given by Prime Minister Jim Bolger.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] The museum rebranded as Voyager New Zealand Maritime Museum in November 2009, in order to reflect the museum's focus on exploration and discovery.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] The organisation's current name, New Zealand Maritime Museum Hui Te Ananui a Tangaroa, was adopted in 2014.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] The organisation's Māori language name, Hui te Ananui a Tangaroa, was gifted by Hugh Kāwharu of Ngāti Whātua Ōrākei, and means "the Dwelling of Tangaroa", the atua of the oceans.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] The establishment of a maritime history museum in Auckland began as a proposal by members of the Auckland Maritime Society, including Bill Laxon, Bob Hawkins, Cliff Hawkins and John Street, and by former members of the Auckland Harbour Board and Union Steam Ship Company.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] The society had been established in 1958 as a section of the Auckland Institute and Museum, focused on promoting the study of ships.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] In 1973, the society explored the possibility of establishing a maritime museum on the shores of Lake Pupuke, which was found to be unsuitable.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] In November 1981, the Auckland Maritime Museum was established as a charitable trust.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] The Auckland Ferry Terminal, where the museum had been storing archival materials, was explored as a potential site for the museum, but due to the cost of renovations this was decided against.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] In 1984, the museum appointed a director, Gordon Stevenson, former director of the Queen Elizabeth II Army Memorial Museum, and had begun exploring the possibility of using sheds on Princes Wharf.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] Plans for a smaller Princes Wharf museum were halted when the Auckland Harbour Board decided to redevelop Hobson Wharf, with the museum becoming a major part of the redevelopment.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] In 1989, Rodney Wilson was appointed as the new director for the museum, who led fundraising efforts to establish the institution.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] Plans for the museum at Hobson Wharf were announced in February 1989, with construction on the museum beginning in mid-1992.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] The museum opened in August 1993, at an estimated cost of NZ$11.1 million.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] Many of the early maritime collections were long-term loans from Auckland War Memorial Museum, or donated items by members of the Auckland Maritime Society.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] While originally focusing on Auckland, the museum later expanded to become a national maritime museum.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] By 1996, financial difficulties led to staff redundancies at the museum, with museum director Richard Cassels resigning during the financial difficulties in 1998.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] In 2001, the New Zealand Government funded the Pacific Discovery Experience, a virtual reality exhibition depicting both the discovery of New Zealand by Polynesian peoples, and the later discovery by Europeans.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] A NZ$8 million extension to the northern end of the museum was built in 2009 to house a permanent exhibition, *Blue Water, Black Magic*, about Sir Peter Blake.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] It includes the original *NZL 32* (*Black Magic*).
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] *Blue Water, Black Magic* was developed in collaboration with Te Papa and Blake's daughter Sarah-Jane Blake.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] In 2010, an extension was added to the museum, housing an exhibition to New Zealand yachting which includes *NZL 32*, the yacht which won the 1995 America's Cup, suspended in the centre of the space.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] By 2018, the museum received approximately 160,000 annual visitors.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] The museum was run by New Zealand National Maritime Museum Trust Board until March 2018, when it became a part of Regional Facilities Auckland, an Auckland Council-controlled organisation.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] The organisation is now run by Tātaki Auckland Unlimited, the economic development agency of Auckland.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] In 2008, the Auckland Regional Amenities Funding Act was established, which ensured that funding for the New Zealand Maritime Museum was spread across all local councils in the Auckland Region.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] As of 2021, funding for the organisation primarily comes from the Auckland Council.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] The first director of the Auckland Maritime Museum Trust was Gordon Stevenson, who was employed in January 1985.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] Rodney Wilson became the museum director in 1989, who was the director of the museum when it opened in 1993.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] In 1994, Wilson left to become the director of the Auckland War Memorial Museum.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] Wilson was replaced by Richard Cassels in the same year, who left in 1998.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] Cassels was followed by chief executive Larry Robbins in 1999, Craig Hobbs in 2007, and Paul Evans in 2008.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] By 2013, Murray Reade had become the chief executive officer.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] In 2013, former director of Toitū Otago Settlers Museum, Linda Wigley, became the director of the maritime museum, overseeing the redevelopment of the museum until her resignation in June 2014.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] The current director of the maritime museum, Vincent Lipanovich, has held the position since 2015.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] In 2018, the institution had 166 volunteers, working as tour guides, maintenance and operational crew for heritage vessels, model makers and learning programme assistants.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] Since 2003, personnel from the Royal New Zealand Navy have been occasionally seconded to the museum to assist with maintenance of the ships and exhibition objects.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] In addition, the museum holds collection items focusing on subjects including whaling, modern commercial shipping, lifeboat, pilotage and coastguard services, marine surveying, maritime arts and crafts and maritime recreation.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] The museum also operates *Aotearoa One*, launched 2013, described on the museum's website as "a modern take on a traditional waka", which no longer has scheduled sailings.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] The museum previously operated the *Rapaki steam crane*, a 1926 floating steam crane, built at Paisley in Scotland for the Lyttelton Harbour Board, which was permanently removed and dismantled in December 2018.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] The vessel had been used in active service for three years during World War II, being used to support the United States Navy at New Caledonia.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] The museum has a collection of over 130 watercraft, including the 1933 John L.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] Hacker-designed mahogany and kauri speedboat *Jon-El*, *The Frances*, an early 20th century vessel owned by the Shakespear family, and Paul Caffyn's kayak *Isadora*.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] Other vessels include the *Tainui*, an 1860 whaling vessel, P-class sailing dinghies designed by Harry Highet, *Mammoth*, a moth-class dinghy, and the Karlich hull used by Olympic Gold medalist rowers, the 1972 New Zealand eight.
[src:alingano-maisu/aotearoa-one] *Tatarai*, a Baurua voyager canoe from Kiribati built in 1976 by Kiribati islanders and photographer Jim Siers using traditional methods, and sailed from Kiribati to Fiji in 1976, is also held in the museum's collections.
[src:alingano-maisu/apilan] Apilan is a native Malay word, not descended from any foreign word.
[src:alingano-maisu/apilan] It is also a standalone word, because the syllable is api-lan instead of apil-an.
[src:alingano-maisu/apilan] The term comes from Malay word *kota* which in turn comes from the Sanskrit word कोट्ट (kota) which means fort, fortress, castle, fortified house, fortification, works, city, town, or place encircled by walls.
[src:alingano-maisu/apilan] The word *mara* may come from Malay word meaning "appear before", "forward", "come", "moved to the front", "forward", and "advanced".
[src:alingano-maisu/apilan] Thus it can be interpreted as "breastwork before a cannon" or "breastwork at the front".
[src:alingano-maisu/apilan] According to the Great Indonesian Dictionary (KBBI), kota mara means (1) Wall on a ship to protect men mounting the cannon (2) Terrace or wall over a castle which a cannon is mounted.
[src:alingano-maisu/apilan] Warington Smyth, kota mara means transverse deck bulkhead at stem and stern (of a ship).
[src:alingano-maisu/apilan] *Benteng* itself means fort, battery, or redoubt.
[src:alingano-maisu/apilan] Singapore resident John Crawfurd recorded Malay piracy near Singapore waters.
[src:alingano-maisu/apilan] The Malay pirate ships of the time were 40–50 feet (12–15 m) long with 15-foot (4.6 m) beam.
[src:alingano-maisu/apilan] The decks were made of split *nibong* wood.
[src:alingano-maisu/apilan] Smaller pirate craft put up thick plank bulwarks [apilan] when fighting, while larger ones like those of the Lanun people had bamboo ledges hanging over their gunwales, with a protecting breastwork [kota mara] of plaited rattan about 3 feet (0.91 meters) high.
[src:alingano-maisu/apilan] A crew might consist of 20–30 men, augmented with oarsmen of captured slaves.
[src:alingano-maisu/apilan] Small craft would have nine oars per side; larger ones would be double-banked, with an upper tier of oarsmen seated on the bulwark projection hidden behind rattan breastwork.
[src:alingano-maisu/apilan] Pirate armament included a stockade near the bow, with iron or brass 4-pounders, and another stockade aft, generally with two swivel guns.
[src:alingano-maisu/apilan] They also might have four or five brass swivels, or rantaka, on each side.
[src:alingano-maisu/apilan] They have bamboo shields, and were armed with spears, keris, muskets and other firearms they could get.
[src:alingano-maisu/ote-a] The **ʻōteʻa** (usually written as *otea*) is a traditional dance and accompanying music from Tahiti characterized by a rapid hip-shaking motion to percussion accompaniment.
[src:alingano-maisu/ote-a] The dancers, standing in several rows, may be further choreographed to execute different figures (including tamau, varu, otamu, ami, and fa'arapu) while maintaining the hip-shaking.
[src:alingano-maisu/ote-a] The hip motion itself may in some choreographies be synchronized amongst multiple dancers and may be further coordinated with the accompanying percussion arrangement.
[src:alingano-maisu/ote-a] The dance is with music only (drums) at a fast rhythm, and no singing.
[src:alingano-maisu/ote-a] The drum can be one of the different types of the *tōʻere*, a lying log of wood with a longitudinal slit, which is struck by one or two sticks.
[src:alingano-maisu/ote-a] Additional drum types accompanying the dance may include the ng drum covered with a shark skin and struck by the hands or with sticks) played at a slower rhythm, or the smaller *faʻatētē* drum.
[src:alingano-maisu/ote-a] The ʻōteʻa is one of the few dances which already existed in pre-European times as a male dance.
[src:alingano-maisu/ote-a] (The *hura* (Tahitian vernacular for hula), a dance for women, on the other hand has disappeared, and likewise is gone the couple's dance ʻupaʻupa but which may have reemerged as the tāmūrē).
[src:alingano-maisu/ote-a] Nowadays, however the ʻōteʻa can be danced by men (ʻōteʻa tāne), by women (ʻōteʻa vahine), or by both genders (ʻōteʻa ʻāmui = united ʻō.).
[src:alingano-maisu/ote-a] Dancers of the ʻōteʻa make gestures reenacting daily occupations of life.
[src:alingano-maisu/ote-a] For the men the gestural themes can be chosen from warfare or sailing, and then they may use spears or paddles.
[src:alingano-maisu/ote-a] For women the gestural themes are typically closer to home or from nature: hand gestures suggesting combing their hair, or the flight of a butterfly.
[src:alingano-maisu/ote-a] More elaborate themes have been adopted; for example one where the dancers end up in a map of Tahiti, highlighting important places.
[src:alingano-maisu/ote-a] In a proper ʻōteʻa the story of the theme should pervade the whole dance.
[src:alingano-maisu/ote-a] The costumes are extremely elaborate, typically incorporating long plant fiber ("grass") skirts, belting with tassels that accentuate the hip-motion, may further include decorated headpieces, and may be color-coordinated across the dancers of the company.
[src:alingano-maisu/ote-a] The same *more* dress and the same shaking of the knees for the boys and of the hips for the girls as in all Tahitian dances (see tāmūrē) is used here too.
[src:alingano-maisu/ote-a] Interpretations of the **ʻōteʻa** are frequently included as part of larger Polynesian dance recitals presented at luaus and visitor-oriented live shows in the Hawaiian Islands and other Pacific-rim resorts outside Tahiti.
[src:alingano-maisu/ote-a] Modern drum accompaniments may include drums of European or non-Pacific construction, improvised percussion instruments of modern materials (e.g. high-density polyethylene or metallic commercial food packaging), and the use of prerecorded drum reinforcement soundtracks.
[src:alingano-maisu/upa-upa] The **ʼupaʼupa** (often written as **upa upa**) is a traditional dance from Tahiti.
[src:alingano-maisu/upa-upa] It was mentioned by European explorers, who described it as very indecent.
[src:alingano-maisu/upa-upa] It is not quite clear how similar the gestures at that time were with the now immensely popular tāmūrē.
[src:alingano-maisu/upa-upa] In both dances the performers form groups of pairs of a boy and a girl, dancing more or less in sexually oriented movements.
[src:alingano-maisu/upa-upa] The musical setting usually includes voice, flute, and drums.
[src:alingano-maisu/upa-upa] After having arrived on Tahiti in 1797, the LMS missionaries quickly intimidated the local rulers of the island and fixed themselves in a position of power.
[src:alingano-maisu/upa-upa] Although this enabled them to abolish such habits as infanticide, cannibalism and tribal wars, it also enabled them to introduce the idea of sin, which was unknown on Tahiti until then.
[src:alingano-maisu/upa-upa] The joy of dancing, so dear to the Polynesian heart, was one of the first to be axed.
[src:alingano-maisu/upa-upa] The famous Pōmare code of 1819 declared the ʼupaʼupa (and tattooing in the same line) to be bad and immoral habitudes, severely to be opposed.
[src:alingano-maisu/upa-upa] In the code of 1842 many restrictions were relaxed, but the ʼupaʼupa (the general term for dancing then) remained on the black list.
[src:alingano-maisu/upa-upa] In the same year the French proclaimed the protectorate.
[src:alingano-maisu/upa-upa] Being Catholic with some broader views on life than the Protestants, and considering that "if you cannot beat them, join them", they proclaimed in the official bulletin of 1849 that the ʼupaʼupa was still forbidden, except on public feastdays, but then still without the indecent gestures.
[src:alingano-maisu/upa-upa] The act of 1853, repeated in 1876 was more restrictive.
[src:alingano-maisu/upa-upa] In the hope that the Tahitians would spend their time on more pious occupations than dancing and drinking, a system of licenses was introduced.
[src:alingano-maisu/upa-upa] A license could only be obtained by a chef and only on Saturday evenings.
[src:alingano-maisu/upa-upa] Despite all these restrictions, dancing went on, less secret or more secret depending on the law at that moment.
[src:alingano-maisu/upa-upa] Nevertheless, many years of suppression had left a mark on it, and although the idea and the steps were still there, the ʼupaʼupa of the old did not really exist anymore.
[src:alingano-maisu/upa-upa] In the beginning of the 20th century Tahitian dances were only performed on such festivities as 14 July and saw an evolution into what they have become nowadays.
[src:alingano-maisu/upa-upa] Around 1900 the traditional costumes came back, and although they still looked more like mother Hubbard dresses or ponchos, at least they were made of traditional materials.
[src:alingano-maisu/upa-upa] Around 1920 strips of raffia were added, which soon would develop into the characteristic *more* or grass skirt (in reality made from hibiscus fibers) of Tahiti.
[src:alingano-maisu/upa-upa] The bare torso (for men only) became acceptable.
[src:alingano-maisu/upa-upa] Prizes started to be awarded to the best dancers on a festival.
[src:alingano-maisu/upa-upa] But it was not until 1956 that Madeleine Mouʼa organised a dance group, called the *heiva*, of which Teriʼi and Takau, daughters of the last queen of Tahiti became patrons.
[src:alingano-maisu/upa-upa] Finally then traditional dancing had the blessing from the establishment.
[src:alingano-maisu/upa-upa] The opening of Faaʼa International Airport in 1961 and the real start of the tourist industry on Tahiti made all the dances which had come forth from the ʼupaʼupa a part of daily life once more.
